Just sit down and listen...

247
00:21:53.238 --> 00:21:55.658
please. Sir?

248
00:21:58.140 --> 00:22:00.413
For each thousand you invest,
I will repay you with...

249
00:22:00.434 --> 00:22:01.434
Two hundred.

250
00:22:01.478 --> 00:22:02.956
200 kilos of enamelware a month...

251
00:22:03.082 --> 00:22:05.355
to begin in July and to
continue for one year.

252
00:22:05.376 --> 00:22:09.254
After which time, we're even.
That's it. It's very simple.

253
00:22:09.338 --> 00:22:12.299
- Not good enough.
- It's not good enough.

254
00:22:12.424 --> 00:22:14.426
Not good enough?

255
00:22:14.447 --> 00:22:16.602
Look where you're
living. Look where

256
00:22:16.603 --> 00:22:18.701
you've been put.
"Not good enough."

257
00:22:18.722 --> 00:22:21.475
A couple of months ago you'd
be right, not any more.

258
00:22:21.600 --> 00:22:24.645
Money's still money.

259
00:22:26.271 --> 00:22:30.463
No, it is not. That's
why we are here.

260
00:22:30.504 --> 00:22:31.504
Trade goods...

261
00:22:31.506 --> 00:22:34.092
that's the only currency that'll
be worth anything in the ghetto.

262
00:22:34.113 --> 00:22:37.574
Things have changed, my friend.

263
00:22:39.472 --> 00:22:41.328
Did I call this meeting?

264
00:22:41.558 --> 00:22:43.518
You told Mr Stern you
wanted to speak to me.

265
00:22:43.539 --> 00:22:45.874
I'm here. I've made
you a fair offer.

266
00:22:45.895 --> 00:22:50.921
Fair would be a percentage
in the company.

267
00:22:51.985 --> 00:22:55.718
Forget the whole thing. Get out.

268
00:23:00.472 --> 00:23:03.434
How do we know that you
will do what you say?

269
00:23:03.454 --> 00:23:05.102
Because I said I would.

270
00:23:05.123 --> 00:23:07.354
You want a contract? To
be upheld by what court?

271
00:23:07.375 --> 00:23:10.774
I said what I'll do.
That's our contract.

272
00:23:11.307 --> 00:23:13.480
(CONVERSING IN POLISH)

273
00:23:27.459 --> 00:23:32.985
Five, six, seven...

274
00:23:32.986 --> 00:23:36.531
eight, nine...

275
00:23:48.666 --> 00:23:50.999
The standard SS rate
for Jewish skilled

276
00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:52.983
labourers is seven marks a day...

277
00:23:53.004 --> 00:23:55.882
five for unskilled and women.

278
00:23:55.903 --> 00:23:59.052
This is what you pay the
Reich Economic Office.

279
00:23:59.073 --> 00:24:01.742
The Jews themselves
receive nothing.

280
00:24:01.867 --> 00:24:06.246
Poles you pay wages. Generally,
they get a little more.

281
00:24:06.372 --> 00:24:08.916
- Are you listening?
- What was that about the SS?

282
00:24:09.041 --> 00:24:11.251
The rate? The what?

283
00:24:11.377 --> 00:24:12.993
The Jewish worker's salary...

284
00:24:12.994 --> 00:24:14.694
you pay it directly to the
SS, not to the worker.

285
00:24:14.696 --> 00:24:16.882
- He gets nothing.
- But it's less.

286
00:24:16.903 --> 00:24:18.591
It's less than what
I would pay a Pole.

287
00:24:18.592 --> 00:24:19.592
It's less?

288
00:24:19.593 --> 00:24:22.262
That's the point I'm
trying to make.

289
00:24:22.388 --> 00:24:24.932
Poles cost more.

290
00:24:25.683 --> 00:24:29.144
Why should I hire Poles?

291
00:24:29.332 --> 00:24:33.399
An enamelware factory,
over at, Lipowa Street.

292
00:24:33.419 --> 00:24:36.506
It, it, It's owned by a German.

293
00:24:36.527 --> 00:24:40.114
But it's outside the ghetto, so
you can barter for extra goods...

294
00:24:40.135 --> 00:24:41.907
for eggs, I don't
know what you need...

295
00:24:41.949 --> 00:24:43.701
with the Polish workers.
You can't get it here.

296
00:24:43.742 --> 00:24:47.413
Also, he's asking for ten
healthy women for the...

297
00:24:47.449 --> 00:24:49.123
I'm healthy.

298
00:24:49.748 --> 00:24:51.406
Bring your sister, okay?

299
00:24:51.407 --> 00:24:53.501
(SHOUTING ORDERS IN
GERMAN AND POLISH)

300
00:24:58.507 --> 00:25:00.165
You need to convince
them you have a trade...

301
00:25:00.166 --> 00:25:01.823
something valuable
to the war effort.

302
00:25:01.906 --> 00:25:02.906
Like what?

303
00:25:02.907 --> 00:25:04.263
- I'm a musician.
- What if you don't?

304
00:25:04.346 --> 00:25:06.035
Your name goes on a list.

305
00:25:06.036 --> 00:25:07.770
Your name is on the list,
they put you on trucks...

306
00:25:07.808 --> 00:25:09.893
- No, no, no, that's not true.
- You're a musician?

307
00:25:09.977 --> 00:25:10.977
Yeah.

308
00:25:10.978 --> 00:25:12.688
I'd find a good hiding
place if I were you.

309
00:25:12.771 --> 00:25:15.661
I'm not going to hide
like some animal.

310
00:25:15.662 --> 00:25:17.589
There are places to hide.

311
00:25:22.385 --> 00:25:23.678
The next.

312
00:25:23.720 --> 00:25:27.453
I'm a graduate of the
University of Lwow.

313
00:25:27.536 --> 00:25:30.268
I used to work at the
hydroelectric station in Roznow...

314
00:25:30.351 --> 00:25:32.249
Blue card.

315
00:25:35.732 --> 00:25:37.580
I'm gonna get the necessary papers

316
00:25:37.581 --> 00:25:39.757
because this card is
no good any more.

317
00:25:39.840 --> 00:25:42.468
You can stay in this line all day,
you'll still get one of these.

318
00:25:42.551 --> 00:25:46.096
They are no good. You'll have
to leave the line now...

319
00:25:46.180 --> 00:25:48.528
then you'll get a blue
card, a Blauschein,

320
00:25:48.529 --> 00:25:50.768
to say that you are
an essential worker.

321
00:25:50.851 --> 00:25:54.104
I'll get these papers
for you at Pankiewicz.

322
00:25:54.229 --> 00:25:56.398
Pharmacist. Just there, look.

323
00:25:56.419 --> 00:25:58.171
Guess who is here?

324
00:25:58.192 --> 00:26:00.986
Poldek. Enjoying the
weather, Poldek?

325
00:26:01.070 --> 00:26:03.718
- Enjoying the lines?
- Need some shoe polish?

326
00:26:03.739 --> 00:26:06.304
In metal container maybe.

327
00:26:06.742 --> 00:26:08.499
Not essential? I think you

328
00:26:08.500 --> 00:26:11.205
misunderstand the
meaning of the word.

329
00:26:11.226 --> 00:26:13.582
No blue card, sir.
Stand over there.

330
00:26:13.603 --> 00:26:16.418
Move. Next.

331
00:26:16.960 --> 00:26:19.380
What do you mean, "Not essential"?

332
00:26:19.922 --> 00:26:25.698
I teach history and literature.
Since when it's not essential?

333
00:26:30.516 --> 00:26:32.935
He's metal polisher.

334
00:26:39.726 --> 00:26:40.726
It was not right?

335
00:26:40.727 --> 00:26:42.465
It's very good. He's 53 years old.

336
00:26:42.486 --> 00:26:45.781
- It's too new.
- Thank you.

337
00:26:53.935 --> 00:26:56.417
You're crazy. You left
it in your drawer.

338
00:26:56.542 --> 00:26:58.335
How many times have I told you?

339
00:26:58.356 --> 00:27:01.547
Your work certificate, you keep
in your pocket at all times.

340
00:27:01.630 --> 00:27:03.382
And you leave everything
in your drawer.

341
00:27:03.403 --> 00:27:06.093
How many times I've told you?

342
00:27:06.427 --> 00:27:09.847
I'm a metal polisher.

343
00:27:18.022 --> 00:27:21.087
Take the round sheet of tin...

344
00:27:21.108 --> 00:27:25.195
dip it in soap emulsion.

345
00:27:25.216 --> 00:27:29.950
Then place it centrally
in the press.

346
00:27:44.840 --> 00:27:48.552
We obtain the soup
pot. The soup pot.

347
00:27:48.677 --> 00:27:52.014
Soup pot.

348
00:27:52.097 --> 00:27:55.309
Grosz, Mrs Grosz, stay together.

349
00:27:58.979 --> 00:28:01.465
Look, sir, I have ten work permits

350
00:28:01.466 --> 00:28:04.318
here for the German
enamel factory...

351
00:28:04.339 --> 00:28:07.509
and signed by Mr
Bankier and myself.

352
00:28:07.592 --> 00:28:12.409
If it's carbonised,
clean it with a file.

353
00:28:12.534 --> 00:28:17.039
But don't touch both the
electrodes at the same time.

354
00:28:17.060 --> 00:28:20.542
You'll get electrocuted.
Here, have a try.

355
00:28:24.463 --> 00:28:26.840
Roll the metal under the press...

356
00:28:26.861 --> 00:28:29.447
but be very careful unless
you want your fingers...

357
00:28:29.468 --> 00:28:32.721
to become part of the teapot.

358
00:28:33.910 --> 00:28:37.622
- Occupation?
- I'm a writer. I play the flute.

359
00:28:37.643 --> 00:28:41.021
But Moses is a
skilled metalworker.

360
00:28:41.042 --> 00:28:43.524
He can make tin pots.
He can make tanks.

361
00:28:43.607 --> 00:28:45.505
He can make whatever
Mr Schindler asks.

362
00:28:45.588 --> 00:28:48.237
He's highly skilled.
Give him your card.

363
00:28:48.258 --> 00:28:50.948
Moses, give him your card.

364
00:28:52.574 --> 00:28:58.101
Now, dip the basin with the
tongs into the enamel solution.

365
00:28:59.477 --> 00:29:01.785
And after swivelling it around,

366
00:29:01.786 --> 00:29:04.691
carefully place it
aside to drip-dry.

367
00:29:07.110 --> 00:29:09.183
And whatever he asks
you, allow me just

368
00:29:09.184 --> 00:29:11.051
to represent you
and speak for you.

369
00:29:11.135 --> 00:29:12.928
Don't say a word.

370
00:29:13.012 --> 00:29:16.557
Filing, billing, keeping track
of my appointments, shorthand.

371
00:29:16.578 --> 00:29:19.451
Typing, obviously.
How is your typing?

372
00:29:19.452 --> 00:29:20.644
All right.

373
00:29:20.728 --> 00:29:22.730
Please.

374
00:30:15.741 --> 00:30:19.453
You need a secretary. Pick one.

375
00:30:19.578 --> 00:30:24.458
I don't know how. They're
all so... qualified.

376
00:30:24.583 --> 00:30:27.461
You have to choose.

377
00:30:29.755 --> 00:30:32.549
Big smile, big smile.

378
00:30:53.612 --> 00:30:56.490
If you would, look after my guest.

379
00:30:56.615 --> 00:31:01.516
Boxed teas are good.
Coffee, pâté...

380
00:31:01.537 --> 00:31:05.457
kielbasa sausage,
cheeses, Beluga caviar...

381
00:31:05.541 --> 00:31:07.584
and, of course, who could live
without German cigarettes?

382
00:31:07.605 --> 00:31:10.170
Get me as many as you can find.

383
00:31:10.295 --> 00:31:12.256
And some more fresh fruit.

384
00:31:12.339 --> 00:31:15.301
The real rarities, oranges,
lemons, pineapples.

385
00:31:15.384 --> 00:31:17.803
I need several boxes of
Cuban cigars. The best.

386
00:31:17.928 --> 00:31:19.164
And dark unsweetened chocolate...

387
00:31:19.200 --> 00:31:21.557
not in the shape of ladyfingers,
the chunk chocolate.

388
00:31:21.598 --> 00:31:24.648
Big as my hand, you
sample at wine tastings.

389
00:31:24.685 --> 00:31:28.022
We're going to need lots of
cognac. The best, Hennessy.

390
00:31:28.105 --> 00:31:33.110
Dom Perignon champagne.
Get L'espadon sardines...

391
00:31:33.152 --> 00:31:37.031
and, oh, try to find
nylon stockings.

392
00:31:39.325 --> 00:31:42.578
It is my distinct
pleasure to announce...

393
00:31:42.661 --> 00:31:48.354
the fully operational status
of German enamel factory...

394
00:31:49.043 --> 00:31:53.047
manufacturers of superior
enamelware crockery...

395
00:31:53.276 --> 00:31:58.552
expressly designed and
crafted for military use.

396
00:31:58.677 --> 00:32:01.347
Utilising only the most
modern equipment...

397
00:32:01.430 --> 00:32:03.886
D.E.F.'s staff of
highly skilled and

398
00:32:03.887 --> 00:32:06.477
experienced artisans
and journeymen...

399
00:32:06.602 --> 00:32:10.105
deliver a product of
unparalleled quality...

400
00:32:10.230 --> 00:32:14.151
enabling me to proffer, with
absolute confidence and pride...

401
00:32:14.276 --> 00:32:16.820
a full line of field
and kitchenware...

402
00:32:16.945 --> 00:32:20.991
unsurpassable in all
respects by my competitors.

403
00:32:21.116 --> 00:32:24.328
See attached list and
available colours.

404
00:32:24.828 --> 00:32:28.582
Anticipating the enclosed bids
will meet with your approval...

405
00:32:28.603 --> 00:32:32.503
looking forward to a long and
mutually prosperous association...

406
00:32:32.628 --> 00:32:35.735
I extend to you in advance
my sincerest gratitude...

407
00:32:35.756 --> 00:32:38.842
and very best regards.
Oskar Schindler.

408
00:32:38.968 --> 00:32:42.346
Yeah, I need 700 gross from
here for next Thursday.

409
00:32:42.471 --> 00:32:45.182
Nine hundred, no, make
it ten for Wednesday.

410
00:32:45.307 --> 00:32:48.003
All this stuff here
goes to Madritsch's

411
00:32:48.004 --> 00:32:50.229
factory on Tuesday of next week.

412
00:33:04.994 --> 00:33:08.372
My father was fond of saying, "You
need three things in life..."

413
00:33:08.497 --> 00:33:13.064
"a good doctor, a
forgiving priest..."

414
00:33:13.085 --> 00:33:15.879
"and a clever accountant."

415
00:33:19.341 --> 00:33:23.304
The first two, I've
never had much use for.

416
00:33:23.470 --> 00:33:26.890
But the third.

417
00:33:32.208 --> 00:33:36.337
Just pretend, for Christ's sake.

418
00:33:39.570 --> 00:33:42.573
Is that all?

419
00:33:47.369 --> 00:33:50.581
I'm trying to thank you.

420
00:33:50.914 --> 00:33:54.835
I'm saying I couldn't have
done this without you.

421
00:33:57.379 --> 00:34:00.257
The usual thing would be to
acknowledge my gratitude.

422
00:34:00.382 --> 00:34:05.220
It would also, by the way,
be the courteous thing.

423
00:34:05.304 --> 00:34:08.057
You're welcome.

424
00:34:17.086 --> 00:34:19.485
Get out of here.

425
00:34:32.665 --> 00:34:35.876
Klonowska, who is it?

426
00:34:45.177 --> 00:34:48.347
She's so embarrassed. Look at her.

427
00:34:59.900 --> 00:35:02.111
You know something?
You would like her.

428
00:35:02.194 --> 00:35:04.196
- Oskar, please.
- What?

429
00:35:04.279 --> 00:35:06.657
I don't have to like her...
just because you do.

430
00:35:06.782 --> 00:35:09.451
It doesn't work that way.

431
00:35:22.610 --> 00:35:25.175
You've done well here.

432
00:35:27.636 --> 00:35:30.180
You look wonderful.

433
00:35:32.975 --> 00:35:37.563
- Be careful of the step, miss.
- Mrs Schindler, Marek.

434
00:35:49.241 --> 00:35:51.318
It's not a charade, all this?

435
00:35:51.319 --> 00:35:53.933
Charade? How could
it be a charade?

436
00:35:53.996 --> 00:35:55.249
The clothes, the
car, the apartment.

437
00:35:55.250 --> 00:35:56.250
Wait a minute.

438
00:35:56.251 --> 00:35:58.980
Take a guess how many
people are on my payroll.

439
00:35:58.981 --> 00:36:00.232
Oskar.

440
00:36:00.252 --> 00:36:05.403
My father, at the height of his
success, had 50. I've got 350.

441
00:36:05.487 --> 00:36:10.054
350 workers on the factory
floor, with one purpose.

442
00:36:10.179 --> 00:36:12.181
To make pots and pans?

443
00:36:12.264 --> 00:36:16.185
To make money. For me.

444
00:36:21.940 --> 00:36:26.090
Does anyone ask about me?

445
00:36:26.612 --> 00:36:32.889
Back home? Everybody.
All the time.

446
00:36:36.851 --> 00:36:39.483
They won't soon forget the name

447
00:36:39.484 --> 00:36:42.711
Schindler here, I
can tell you that.

448
00:36:43.316 --> 00:36:46.590
"Oskar Schindler" they'll say.

449
00:36:46.632 --> 00:36:50.260
"Everybody remembers him."

450
00:36:50.448 --> 00:36:54.556
"He did something extraordinary."

451
00:36:55.161 --> 00:36:59.770
"He did something
no one else did."

452
00:37:00.229 --> 00:37:06.026
"He came here with
nothing, a suitcase...

453
00:37:06.193 --> 00:37:12.199
"and built a bankrupt company
into a major manufactory."

454
00:37:12.324 --> 00:37:15.452
"And left with a steamer trunk..."

455
00:37:15.577 --> 00:37:20.124
"two steamer trunks
full of money."

456
00:37:20.499 --> 00:37:24.420
"All the riches of the world."

457
00:37:26.630 --> 00:37:30.009
It's comforting to see
that nothing's changed.

458
00:37:30.134 --> 00:37:33.470
You're wrong, Emilie.

459
00:37:34.075 --> 00:37:36.598
There's no way I could have
known this before but...

460
00:37:36.661 --> 00:37:39.476
there was always
something missing.

461
00:37:39.664 --> 00:37:43.647
In every business I tried, I can
see now, it wasn't me that failed.

462
00:37:43.731 --> 00:37:46.483
Something was missing.

463
00:37:46.650 --> 00:37:48.424
Even if I'd known
what it was, there's

464
00:37:48.425 --> 00:37:50.154
nothing I could have
done about it...

465
00:37:50.237 --> 00:37:54.825
because you can't
create this thing.

466
00:37:54.950 --> 00:37:57.697
And it makes all the
difference in the

467
00:37:57.698 --> 00:38:00.164
world between success and failure.

468
00:38:01.060 --> 00:38:02.833
Luck?

469
00:38:05.294 --> 00:38:08.172
War.

470
00:38:31.654 --> 00:38:35.366
Should I stay?

471
00:38:36.012 --> 00:38:39.265
It's a beautiful city.

472
00:38:40.287 --> 00:38:44.521
I asked you if I should stay.

473
00:38:45.855 --> 00:38:48.295
It's up to you.

474
00:38:52.299 --> 00:38:56.887
Promise me, Oskar. No doorman or
maitre d' will ever presume...

475
00:38:56.971 --> 00:39:02.351
I'm anyone other than Mrs
Schindler, and I'll stay.

476
00:39:04.603 --> 00:39:06.814
Goodbye, darling.

477
00:39:23.455 --> 00:39:25.548
I could try to read
this or I could

478
00:39:25.549 --> 00:39:27.584
eat my lunch while it's still hot.

479
00:39:27.935 --> 00:39:29.166
We're doing well?

480
00:39:29.186 --> 00:39:30.563
- Yes.
- Better this month than last?

481
00:39:30.584 --> 00:39:31.584
Yes.

482
00:39:31.658 --> 00:39:33.379
Any reason to think next
month will be worse?

483
00:39:33.380 --> 00:39:36.135
The war could end.

484
00:39:46.645 --> 00:39:49.189
- What?
- There is a machinist outside...

485
00:39:49.210 --> 00:39:52.359
who'd like to thank you
personally for giving him a job.

486
00:39:52.484 --> 00:39:54.737
Every day he comes. He's very

487
00:39:54.738 --> 00:39:57.614
grateful. It'll
just take a minute.

488
00:40:03.454 --> 00:40:05.873
Mr Lowenstein.

489
00:40:12.775 --> 00:40:15.883
I want to thank you, sir...

490
00:40:15.966 --> 00:40:18.656
for giving me the
opportunity to work.

491
00:40:18.740 --> 00:40:21.722
You're welcome. I'm sure
you're doing a great job.

492
00:40:21.847 --> 00:40:26.101
The SS beat me up. They
would have killed me...

493
00:40:26.498 --> 00:40:30.856
but I am essential to the
war effort, thanks to you.

494
00:40:30.939 --> 00:40:32.941
That's great.

495
00:40:33.025 --> 00:40:35.298
I work hard for you.

496
00:40:35.381 --> 00:40:36.757
